segments.text: And those particular jokes were excluded from that issue.
The battalion in those days did not see its role as primarily investigative journalism, I assume.
What did you all think the purpose was of the battalion?
Well, it was the official newspaper of College Station.
They would give us, I think, their legal ads.
And we would print them.
And then of course it got some, we had also national advertising, that's how we made it, the national advertising, primarily cigarettes that were
allocated just to the newspaper without much solicitation.
Then we had local advertisers, too, that came in there.
And we could write editorials, and we'd have letters to the editor and things like that.
Did you all ever have a tangle with the administration over any issue?
Other than the jokes?
No, the jokes, that's the last one, because that was a non-winner.
Now, at the time you were an undergraduate, is Dr. Walton the president?
President.
Describe him as president.
He was an excellent speaker and a fine gentleman.
During that last year,
He gave us a one-hour credit course where we would go once a week to listen to his lecture on current affairs or something like that.
And he had actual contact with the student body.
As I recall, it was an elective course, but he would come and lecture himself.
Now, and he had been at A&M a long time, hadn't he?
A long time.
So that he knew the student body and so forth.
They lived on campus in the...
In the old... President's house west of Sabeasa.
Yeah.
And I presume that you had known him and he had known you for a number of years.
That would be true.
In fact, I remember...
as just a kid growing up, I would sell magazines through Crowell Publishing Company, who had Woman's Home, Compadion, Collier's, and American Magazine.
And I would sell those on the campus, and I would also

call on the ladies, and I remember Mrs. Walton and I would, she would be interested in the Woman's Home Companion, and I can always recall that that was the first air conditioning on the campus, in fact, it was their home.
And it was really something extraordinary to
call on her and feel that cool air coming out.
Back to your student days, if you needed counseling, if you needed advising when you were an A&M undergraduate, to whom did you turn?
I don't think they had any local, I mean any student
Counseling, you could turn to the TAC officer for your particular organization.
We had Colonel Bennett, Major Breland, and Major Hudson.
They were Coast artillerymen.
You could consult with them.
I don't know of any formal.
There wasn't an assistant or associate dean of arts and sciences that you went over to?
For academics, maybe, or the head of the department.
You could consult with him academically, but there was no formal.
The only thing that I recall when I went through was that your freshman year you had a,
a battery of tests that you took, and I guess they were put on your record someplace in the registrar's office.
Somebody could use to advise you if you were changing courses or something like that.
Were you listed officially as a history major?
No, liberal arts.
Just liberal arts?
I majored in history and minored in English.
Okay.
So many hours for a major, so many hours for a minor.
And the YMCA, what did you and other students, what role did it play in your activity, your life?
Well, it was not so much if you had some kind of local,
Church affiliation, you know, most of the cadets or students would join their church, you know, from their family church when they came to A&M.
And on a Sunday morning, it was just a sea of khaki coming out of the North Gate back to the campus.
Now, did you go to church on Sunday with your family or with your buddies?
I went to church at the First Baptist Church and would see student friends and Father.
But, I mean, did you walk over there with your friends?
Oh, yeah, yeah.
And you were allowed to sit with them and not with Mom and Dad?
Oh, yeah, I didn't have to.
But those were student churches.
Wasn't the YMCA also a center for activities other than the YMCA building?
Yes, they had the YMCA Council, and that was made up of students.
The only other religious activity they had was a religious emphasis week sometime in the spring, as I recall, shortly after classes resumed from the holidays.
They would have a week-long
session of visiting ministers that would come in and they would have a convocation each day at 11 o'clock or something like that.
And then they had emphasis with the local churches.
Did you and your buddies participate in that pretty well?
We'd go hear the lecture or the formal.
And that was in Guyon Hall?
Guyon Hall, old Guyon Hall.
What else occurred in Guyon Hall?
Well, at one time, when I was there, after World War II, they made a movie theater out of it.
But it was not in your day?
Not in our day.
We had the Assembly Hall, the old Assembly Hall over there behind Law and Puryear, before we get to Law and Puryear.
Do you remember any great movies, great in your memory that you saw at the Assembly Hall?
Oh, no, I can't.

I guess, I don't recall, except they had on Sunday afternoon a free movie at one o'clock, you know, and you could, that was for the entire corps, and if you were lucky, well, you could, you know, slip in there and
Well, they didn't charge.
It was a free move.
As I'm turning through some of my kind of routine questions, do you remember in your undergraduate days any famous visitors to the campus?
President Roosevelt.
No, that wasn't during my undergraduate days.
That was in the 30s.
President Roosevelt came because his...

son was on the board of directors as i recall was it elliot or i believe i believe it was elliot from who lived in fort worth or someplace maybe i don't know anyway he made a visit and i recall that of course he came by train and uh yeah of course he he'd been an invalid like he was you couldn't take any pictures
But I do know that there was a, on the reviewing stand, on the drill field, that when the Corps passed in review for him, that they had a specially made handrail for him to stand.
I think he just came at noon and left at 3 or something like that on some kind of a tour.
Now, were you and your family aware of how physically
handicapped he was then?
I was not as a little kid.
I don't think anybody was actually because they really protected that affliction all through his career.
As far as you recall, he did not then make a formal speech.
He did a review?
I don't recall.
But I do know that he did review the cadet corps.
Other famous visitors you remember during your undergraduate days?
Well, there weren't too many.
They all came afterwards.
Oh, yeah, I do remember.
I've seen a year.
We had two, well, they weren't dignitaries, they were just ex-A&M officers.
Ensign Gay was a member of A Battery Coast.
After he was rescued from the Pacific, he made a visit to the campus.
Really?
And he was still an ensign at the time.
And he visited around in the Corps.
And at the same time, a B-25 pilot in Doolittle's raid over Japan named Hilger, he was an older graduate of A&M, he returned to the campus.
And that was in the summer of 42.
And famous visitors, what about some of the orchestras and other men?
Oh, we had for the Grove, the inauguration of the Grove, which was a little social place in that summer, we had the famous Ina Rae Hutton All-Girl Orchestra.
They came and played for that.
And then there were some good orchestras that came to A&M for core dances during those times.
But, you know, I'd have to be... Oh, and of course that time also they were making this movie, We've Never Been Licked.
That was during the summer of 42.
when we had the corps for the movie take would have to assemble every afternoon for a week, and that got boring and tiresome.
In fact, by the end of the week, the ranks were rather slim.
But let's see, who was that?
Robert Mitchum.
Robert Mitchum.
Anne... Bancroft?
Martha O'Driscoll was one.
So you were a movie star then because you were out there in that movie, weren't you?
For a couple of days I was, and then I left it.
Do you remember your impression when you first saw that movie?
Well, you tried to recall where you were, if you could point yourself out and all, and I
In fact, I've got a copy at home now that I got way, way, I mean, just a few years ago.
It was a little corny, actually.
It had an amazing seeming, pretty authentic in places.
But didn't you and your fellow students think that you were being part of something patriotic?
Oh, yeah, yeah, absolutely.
How much did...
The best thing about that show was I believe they had the true Reveille in it.
The little black doll.
The true Reveille.
When did... Let's sidelight on Reveille.
As far as you're aware, when did the first Reveille come to the campus?
As I...
Remember the story, some students were coming back from Navasota one night or one afternoon and they saw this injured animal on the road or something.
They picked her up and brought her back to the campus.
Was that in your elementary school days?
No, I think that was about in high school days.
Oh, okay.
Shortly before I entered A&M.
All right, while we're on that tradition, while you were, before you went away to World War II, do you remember Muster, Aggie Muster?
You know, that's a good question.
I don't want to be disrespectful, but I don't think that it really was reinstituted or came about until they observed it during the war at Corregidor.
I agree with your impression.
I think that it was...
quite modest until World War II, and then, all right.
The only thing that I could associate with it would be that on November the 11th, which was Armistice Day for World War I, the cadet colonel's staff would place a wreath at the
monument on the campus to the World War I dead.
But I just, you know, I just don't recall it.
All right.
Describe bonfire during your undergraduate days.
It was a trash fire.
The main activity was reclaiming wood or buildings or outhouses primarily that should not be burned.
And it was held on what is now the drill field in front of the MSC.
Correct.
And who gathered up all of that rubbish?
Students.
Was it all students?
Prowling.
Now, they may have had some trees or limbs or rubbish or something like that delivered there, but it just came about.
It wasn't near the...
activity that now.
And was there a gathering of pretty well the whole student body and speeches and so forth?
That was the most interesting was to listen to old Yale leaders come back and make a speech or to hear somebody like P.L.
Downs Jr. who was a
Big Aggie would make a speech, you know.
The football team would make a speech.
And that was more interesting than going through all this activity and building a huge bonfire.
All right, you mentioned Pinky.
He was not yet back in College Station full-time, was he, when you were an undergraduate?
When I got here in 1959, he was here full-time on the campus.
On the campus.
I believe that's correct.

And I've been told by a few people that they think that Pinky deserves most of the credit for using the thumbs-up signal for Gig'Em, that that was the old symbol for the yell aimed particularly at TCU, to gig those frogs.
that there was a Rice Yale and an SMU Yale and so forth.
As I recall, that motion was given by the Yale leaders when they, one, two, three, to be associated.
You could be correct about that.
I don't know.
Let's see.
But it's just like this whoop.
That didn't occur in my day.
I didn't know.
That's relatively new.
Well, and within the last 15, 18 years, the waving of the white towel.
Oh, that's new.
Then the yell, which I don't like at all, beat the hell out of.
That started in the late 70s.
No, I think that we used to say that.
Oh, did you?
Oh, okay.
We used to tell out of so-and-so, and that, I think, could be attributed to the yellator named Buster Keaton way back there in the 39-40 in that era.
But, of course, you know, one thing that I'd like to see bring back would be the
the block tee that the Cadet Corps made at football games.
Yes, yes.
And that's where that you would have a handkerchief would be white and then you'd pick up a red flag and you could alternate those.
You see that?
That was pretty good.
But I don't guess they've attempted that in years.
I don't remember it.
Do you remember ever seeing it?
Yes, a long time ago.
When you were an undergraduate, other than the Corps of Cadets, what were the other student organizations that were most respected, most admired?
Well, I want to say that they had a scholarship honor society.
Now, it didn't take a whole lot to get in there, but you did have to be a distinguished student for so many semesters or something like that.
And to be a distinguished student on the three-point system, you had to have a 2.25.
That was an organization that had good students in it.
The other one, I guess, would be the Letterman's Association, which would be the athletic group.
What did you and your fellow students think about the band and the singing cadets?
The band was recognized.
It wasn't the Fightin' Texas Aggie Band.
It was the band, you see.
The senior cadets were good.
It was very voluntary.
And they didn't have the uniforms that they do now and the trips that they make and the promotion that they did get.
But it started way back there then.
Mr. Wolcott, I remember, he put a whole lot of time into that.
Let's see.
Do you know whether or not there were any secret fraternities in existence when you were a student?
When I was a student, I did not know of any organization.
I came to learn later
that there may have been some that existed for any number of years.
But I don't know.
I have learned that apparently the stickers or the swastikas goes back at least to the 20s.
The swastikas.
And the TTs apparently go back fairly far also.
And as far as I can learn about
Almost their total activity was designed to get their own members into key positions, that there was nothing negative, that it was to try to encourage positive leadership.
Let's see.
Senior Boots, where did you get yours and how much did they cost?
Hollick Boot Shop, Northgate.
As I recall,
They were about $80 or $90.
Which was a lot of money.
Well, at that time, I don't know what they cost now.
I have no idea.
And how did you feel when you first put them on?
Well, you felt pretty good because at that time, let's see, you had...
Between your junior and...
I mean, your sophomore and junior year, you discarded...
government-issue uniform and put on a tailored uniform that you had gotten, you see.
Juniors, you start wearing cuffs, of course.
Then they went out during the war and wore greens and a blouse.
And then your senior year, you could wear boots or
ice cream trousers, we called them.
That's the only thing that I recall about it.
Everything was leading up to where you could use that blouse, your senior blouse, if you were commissioned later on.
Now, in terms of status, what student office was the most sought, the most admired?
Was it Corps Commander?
Cadet Colonel.
Cadet.
All right.
Ross Volunteers, they existed then?
They did.
They did.
It was...
Strictly kind of an elective and voluntary, you could get into it.
They were more or less social, primarily social, actually, because they had one whole weekend where they had dances and parties.
What about yell leaders?
They were elected.
Let's see.
The top, I guess, would be cadet colonel, and then we had a position of president of the senior class, head yell leader.
Those were particular positions that were
Salt.
Describe, as far as you recall, the project houses and what they meant to A&M students.
Well, the project houses were the baby of Dr. Dan Russell, who organized them, and it meant a whole lot to the college.
provided an opportunity for guys to come down and go to school on a cooperative basis.
And I remember some members over there, well, one of the more recent ones that we recall is Reagan Brown was in the project houses.
And there were a lot of good students that went through that.
Was there any kind of stigma attached to it?
None whatsoever.
In fact, the American Legion had its own house, too.
They built one.
It's torn down now, but the project houses were uniformly built.
And even before they existed on the campus, they had, I think, a couple here in Bryan.
Did you ever go away for any kind of summer job?
No, sir.
And then what would have been summer ROTC camp for you and your class, you stayed here and went faster.
Did you ever hitchhike?
I have hit tight on occasion, but...
Describe that for an Aggie.
That was quite an opportunity.
That could be where the signal picked up, but it was very controlled.
In other words, if you reached a point, if you put your...
bagged down while you were next in line, and that was respected.
Whoever got there first, there were certain main corners that were used, and of course the famous, what was his name, the famous guy that hitchhiked all over the United States from A&M.
Good gracious.
He made a name for himself.
I've not heard about him, so when you recall his name, we'll add him in the final type version of this.
Did you ever have any negative experience hitchhiking as an Aggie?
I never did.
Did you ever hear of anybody did?
I have not.
I haven't heard of any time when somebody, I've heard of lots of times when they stepped in to assist somebody
You know, but I've never heard of any adverse circumstance where anybody was.
If you were, I understand the East Gate was the place to go north or south.
Was there a special place if we were in Bryan to catch a ride on north?
Let's see.
Well, Highway 6, I'm just thinking at a corner not far from the courthouse going north was a corner.
Okay.
About at 26th Street or 25th Street, something like that.
And going south, 25th Street was a corner there.
at the courthouse going south.
But you know, there were no east and west roads like they are today.
Now, did you ever have a car as an undergraduate?
Never had a car.
In fact, when my freshman year, I think you could have parked the cars in a two-acre lot.
for all the students on campus who had behavior.
Did you have any special out-of-town dates come to the campus when you were an undergraduate?
Yes, I recall for
